This email is sent to the user when they disable a TFA validation method on their account. Available tokens are: [site] and [user]. Common variables are: [site:name], [site:url], [user:display-name], [user:account-name], and [user:mail].

This email is sent to the user when they enable a TFA validation method on their account. Available tokens are: [site] and [user]. Common variables are: [site:name], [site:url], [user:display-name], [user:account-name], and [user:mail].
This encryption method requires a 128 bit key.

Trusted browsers are a method for
      simplifying login by avoiding verification code entry for a set amount of
      time, @time days from marking a browser as trusted. After @time days, to
      log in you'll need to enter a verification code with your username and
      password during which you can again mark the browser as trusted.
Try one of your other enabled validation methods.

Two-factor authentication (TFA) provides
      additional security for your account. With TFA enabled, you log in to
      the site with a verification code in addition to your username and
      password.
